data.enText: an area of ground that is very wet or covered with water and in which plants, trees, etc. are growing

data.chText: 使不堪承受；使疲于应对；使应接不暇
data.enText: to make sb have more of sth than they can deal with

data.chText: 面对纷至沓来的求职申请，这个部门疲于应对。
data.enText: The department was swamped with job applications.

data.chText: 夏天，这个岛上游客熙熙攘攘，人满为患。
data.enText: In summer visitors swamp the island.
to fill or cover sth with a lot of water
The little boat was swamped by the waves.

tr: low land that is seasonally flooded
has more woody plants than a marsh and better drainage than a bog
a situation fraught with difficulties and imponderables
example: he was trapped in a medical swamp
the basement was inundated after the storm

tr: drench or submerge or be drenched or submerged
example: The tsunami swamped every boat in the harbor

value.def: A swamp is an area of very wet land with wild plants growing in it.
If something swamps a place or object, it fills it with water.

example.ex: A rogue wave swamped the boat...
example.tran: 凶猛的海浪淹没了船只。

example.ex: The Ventura river burst its banks, swamping a mobile home park.
example.tran: 本图拉河的河水冲破堤岸，淹没了活动房区。

value.def: If you are swamped by things or people, you have more of them than you can deal with.

example.ex: The railway station was swamped with thousands of families trying to flee the city.
example.tran: 火车站挤满了成千上万想要逃离这座城市的家庭。

value.tran: 使不堪承受;使疲于应对;使应接不暇
